@node AboutMods "About Modules"
@smartwrap


Music modules are files containing descriptions of one or more sounds and a
list of notes and effects to play with them. One popular program which
produces its own type of module is MED, which you may be familiar with as a
user. A later version of MED, called OctaMED, uses similar modules.


Some demos and games use MED or OctaMED modules for music because it is much
easier to use a standard program to make music than to write a special routine
for each tune. So if you can get the module out of the game (a process known
as 'ripping') then you can listen to your favourite game tunes while doing
something else like word-processing or writing a program. However, please note
the @{"legal implications" link Legal} of this.


The limitation of ripping is this: unless you have an Action Replay or similar
cartridge, you can't actually stop the game while its running and rip out data
without disturbing anything. Nevertheless, I have found this ripper software
to be very effective.


Included in this package are a module player - @{"MEDPlay" link MEDPlay} - and a module ripper
- @{"MEDRip" link MEDRip} - plus a few extra bits of software to support them.


Please note that as yet MEDRip is not capable of handling the newest 'MMD2'
module type which OctaMED 5 and later versions can produce. However this
doesn't seem to be common.


@endnode


@node Install "Installation"
@smartwrap


You do not need to install any of the programs in order to use them, but you
may find it useful to do so if you have a hard drive.


If you have Commodore's Installer program, all you need to do is to
double-click the 'Install MEDUtils' icon then follow the instructions you are
given. If you aren't sure whether you have the program, there's no harm in
trying this anyway.


If you don't have Installer, then you will have to copy the programs to your
hard drive by dragging their icons or by using the Shell. (To install all the
programs you can simply drag the drawer icon.)


@endnode


@node MEDPlay
@smartwrap


Those familiar with MEDPlay might want to read the @{"release history" link MEDPlayHistory} for a
summary of changes.


MEDPlay is a simple module player based on the @{"MED" link AboutMods} playroutines. The
advantages it has over other module players are these:


À It's still very small.

À It can be made resident in memory for Shell use.

À It can stop music automatically instead of looping.

À You can stop or change the music being played simply by running MEDPlay
again.

ÀáIt can decompress modules packed with PowerPacker, SFCD/SFHD, and XPK (if
you have the appropriate decompression libraries).


However, it does have a few limitations (no, really? :-), which I hope you
won't find too annoying:


ÀáCan't play MIDI instruments - only synthsounds, 8-bit samples and hybrids.

ÀáCan't play modules which need 1-64 channel mixing.


One of the reasons I had for writing this was for use in disk magazines. (It's
currently used by the Official MED User Group for its magazine, TI.) Although
it can be run from Workbench, MEDPlay is designed for control by Shell
commands and especially by scripts.


Note that you must have asl.library version 36 or better in your LIBS:
directory if you want to run it from the Workbench or use a file requester to
select music modules. This is a standard library which can be found on your
Workbench disk.


MEDPlay can automatically detect and decompress modules packed with the
PowerPacker or SFCD/SFHD routines (as used by OctaMED 5), but to do so it
requires the appropriate libraries to be present - powerpacker.library and
lh.library, respectively. These can be found on the original OctaMED 5 disks
or via the Internet in Aminet archives util/libs/pplib16.lha and
util/pack/LhLib.lha, respectively.


MEDPlay can also decompress modules packed with any XPK library, as long as
you the appropriate XPK library present. There's no support for decryption.
The XPK package can be found in Aminet archive util/pack/xpk_User.lha.


MEDPlayOcta plays modules which need 5-8 channel mixing; the ordinary MEDPlay
program doesn't. So you can save about 6K on your disk if you only play
4-channel modules.


@{u}Shell usage:@{uu}


To start playing a module, or to change some music already playing, type


MEDPlay <file> [MODNUM <n>] [LOOP] [CHIP] [MBEXIT]


where <file> represents the filename of the module, <n> represents a song
number, and text enclosed in square brackets [] is optional. Multiple files
can be supplied, and they will be played in the order specified.


If the LOOP switch is used with a single file, the file will be played in a
loop until it is stopped manually.

If the LOOP switch is used with more than one file, MEDPlay will run through
the sequence of files repeatedly until it is stopped manually.


The MODNUM keyword causes MEDPlay to play just one song from a multi-module.

The CHIP switch forces MEDPlay to load the module into Chip RAM. Normally it
will load modules into Fast RAM if there's enough free.

The MBEXIT switch causes MEDPlay to stop as soon as both mouse buttons are
pressed together. I would discourage the use of this switch as "well-behaved"
programs shouldn't work like this. I only included it for compatibility with
OctaMEDPlayer.


To stop the music prematurely, or to stop a looping piece of music, type


MEDPlay STOP


To use a file requester to start/stop music, just type


MEDPlay


then pick a module or click Cancel to stop. The requester will keep coming
back when each piece of music finishes, until you click Cancel.


You can also stop a single module by pressing Ctrl-C, or you can completely
exit the program by pressing Ctrl-D.


If you intend to use MEDPlay in a script, please see the separate @{"note" link MEDPlayScriptNote}
concerning this.


@{u}Workbench usage:@{uu}


There are three possible ways to start MEDPlay from the Workbench.


1.áIf your modules are saved with icons, you can set their default tool (using
the Workbench 'Information' function) to something like
'Work:MEDUtils/MEDPlay' (this setting would be correct if you have installed
MEDUtils on a partition called 'Work'). Then, when you double-click them,
MEDPlay will be loaded and will then play them.

2.áIf your modules have icons, you can use extended selection to play them.
What this means is, select the first one, then hold down Shift and select any
others, then (keeping Shift held down) double-click MEDPlay's icon.

3.áDouble-click the MEDPlay icon. A file requester will appear. Select the
drawer your modules are stored in. Then select a module and click OK. The
requester will re-appear when the module(s) stop. You can then stop by
clicking Cancel or select a module or modules again to go on playing.


You can stop a module before its natural end by starting MEDPlay from its icon
and clicking Cancel.


@endnode


@node MEDPlayScriptNote "Using MEDPlay in Scripts"
@smartwrap


If you use MEDPlay in a script for a disk magazine or similar, you will need
to run MEDPlay in 'background' with the Run command. If you want to put
something like


MEDPlay intro.mod


in a startup-sequence, e.g.


Echo "Welcome to XYZ disk magazine issue #5!"
MEDPlay intro.mod
LoadWB
EndCLI >NIL:


you will actually need to use the command


Run >NIL: <NIL: MEDPlay >NIL: <NIL: intro.mod


otherwise the Shell window will just stay on the screen and do nothing until
the music finishes.


If MEDPlay is asked to STOP and there isn't actually any music playing, it
will return code 5 (WARN) in case you want your script to check for this.
Obviously if something else goes wrong it will return code 20 (FAIL) which
will terminate your script unless you use the Failat command (see your
Commodore manual for details) to prevent this.


It is advisable to make MEDPlay resident so that it doesn't need to be loaded
from disk every time your scripts call it. If you choose to do this, you must
not crunch MEDPlay as decrunch routines usually crash if they are made
resident. Crunching MEDPlay only saves about 3-4K so this shouldn't be a big
problem.


@endnode


@node MEDPlayHistory "MEDPlay History"
@smartwrap


version 2.10, 19 February 1997


ÀáXPK decompression added.

ÀáSupport for OS 1.2/1.3 removed, saving several hundred bytes.

ÀáSwitched to using asl.library, which is more standard (and my preferred file
requester). If you don't like this, RTPatch will deal with it...

ÀáMEDPlayOcta introduced - this includes the 5-8 channel mixing routine as
well as the standard one.

ÀáSwitched to the latest playroutines, so MEDPlay(Octa) supports MMD2 modules.

ÀáFast-memory play is possible in both versions of MEDPlay.

ÀáMBEXIT implemented, so MEDPlay should now be almost a drop-in replacement
for OctaMEDPlayer. Use of MBEXIT is discouraged though, since MEDPlay provides
a much nicer way to stop a module playing.


version 2.9, 6 February 1996


ÀáFixed SoundTracker-compatible tempos. Songs using the primary tempos 1-10
used to play at a quarter of the correct speed! I don't know how this bug
found its way into the playroutine as I'm sure Teijo didn't put it there and I
don't remember editing that bit myself. I put it down to gremlins, personally.


version 2.8, 25 January 1996


ÀáReally fixed error reporting this time, I think. Version 2.6 would report
some errors twice, but my "solution" to this in v2.7 meant some errors
wouldn't get reported at all!


version 2.7, 23 January 1996


ÀáPowerPacker and SFCD/SFHD decompression added.

ÀáError reporting improved and debugged (I hope).

ÀáShould no longer crash if given a short or corrupt file.


version 2.6, 6 November 1995


ÀáMODNUM keyword implemented as in OctaMEDPlayer.


version 2.5, 14 August 1995


ÀáDouble-quotes are now handled consistently even in the absence of OS 2.0+
and arp.library. I felt that v2.4's approach seriously damaged the program's
compatibility in automated systems e.g. scripts.

ÀáReally fixed library opening - now the LIBS: directory is looked in first,
followed by the current directory (CLI) or tool directory (Workbench).


version 2.4, 31 July 1995


ÀáIf the loop switch is used with multiple files, the sequence of files will
be looped rather than each individual file.

ÀáFixed a small bug in the library opening which probably never caused any
trouble.

ÀáRewrote some of the C code in assembler to save on code size, and removed a
few bits of code which never actually got called.

À Unified the two versions for OS 1.x and OS 2.0+, so all the improvements
made since version 1.0 can now be enjoyed by everyone.

À Arp.library is now required for most Shell use under OS 1.x

ÀáReqtools.library is not opened unless and until any requesters are required
(suggested by Alan Pfeil). This means that if no user intervention is required
(e.g. you are putting MEDPlay in a script on a self-booting disk),
reqtools.library does not need to be available.


version 2.3, May 1995


Not released.

ÀáI can't remember what I changed here - see the entry for v2.4.


version 2.2, November 1994


À Fixed a bug in the code for changing directories - the program often
(usually?) failed inexplicably if started from the Workbench.


version 2.1, September 1994


First public release.

ÀáSupports multi-modules.


version 2.0, April 1994


Not released.

ÀáI 'built in' the MED playroutine (4-channel songs only!).

ÀáSome OS 2.0 features used to save on code size.


version 1.43, January 1994


Released in MEDUtils r1.0 and r1.1 as MEDPlay13.


versions 1.0-1.42, 1993-1994


Not released. I spent all that time just getting the darn thing working!


@endnode


@node MEDRip
@smartwrap


Those familiar with MEDRip might want to read the @{"release history" link MEDRipHistory} for a
summary of changes.


MEDRip is a simple module ripper. This means that it is designed to identify
any @{"MED or OctaMED" link AboutMods} modules in memory, calculate their size, and save them to
disk.


Despite this apparently rather dodgy mode of operation, it should be
completely system-legal as it only reads memory within the bounds of the
memory blocks listed as public memory. This may cause problems if you try
running the program 'Mungwall' at the same time.


It isn't 100% reliable as most games and demos bypass the operating system and
so are liable to have their data corrupted (i.e. destroyed) in the period
between exiting the program and running MEDRip. Also some games intercept
resets and clear their data in memory to prevent ripping. Besides which, not
much game music will be stored in MED or OctaMED format. Note that I have also
produced a ripper for the alternative Tracker modules as part of my ModUtils
package, which may accompany this.


The effectiveness of MEDRip can be improved using @{"MEDAlloc" link MEDAlloc} or
@{"MakeRipperDisk" link MakeRipperDisk}.


Please note that ripping is not always @{"legal" link Legal}.


@{u}Shell usage:@{uu}


To begin searching for modules, type


MEDRip


and wait. When a module is found, brief information about it will be displayed
in the window. If this is gibberish then don't bother saving it - most modules
contain some meaningful text which you will be able to read. To save the
module, type in a filename - e.g. DF0:NiceRayTracedDemoTune - and press
Return. To skip it, just press Return.


When the search is finished, a Shell prompt will reappear.


@{u}Workbench usage:@{uu}


Double-click the MEDRip icon.


When a module is found, brief information about it will be displayed in a
window. If this is gibberish then don't bother saving it! Most modules contain
meaningful text which you will be able to read. To save the module, type in a
filename - e.g. DF0:NiceRayTracedDemoTune - and press Return. To skip it, just
press Return.


When the search is finished, the window will disappear.


@endnode


